00:48:20.480 --> 00:48:26.530
to be great if it goes to 110
but bankrupt if it stays at 50.

00:48:26.530 --> 00:48:29.370
So the question is, how
radical are your forecasts?

00:48:29.370 --> 00:48:35.300
And we try to
anticipate a future that

00:48:35.300 --> 00:48:41.870
looks pretty much like the
norm and make allowance

00:48:41.870 --> 00:48:45.910
for the thing that things
other than the norm can happen.

00:48:45.910 --> 00:48:52.650
And I can't really be much
more concrete than that.

00:48:52.650 --> 00:48:54.995
By the way, all this
stuff is judgment.

00:48:54.995 --> 00:48:56.370
You know, there are no rules.

00:48:56.370 --> 00:48:57.890
There are no algorithms.

00:48:57.890 --> 00:49:00.510
There are no formulas
that always work.

00:49:00.510 --> 00:49:04.520
None of this is any good unless
the person making the decision

00:49:04.520 --> 00:49:06.990
has superior judgment.

00:49:06.990 --> 00:49:08.820
And the first
chapter of the book

00:49:08.820 --> 00:49:11.800
says the most important thing
is second level thinking.

00:49:11.800 --> 00:49:13.397
Most people think
on the first level.

00:49:13.397 --> 00:49:15.980
To be a superior investor, you
must think on the second level.

00:49:15.980 --> 00:49:18.390
You have to think different
from everybody else.

00:49:18.390 --> 00:49:21.870
But in being different,
you have to be better.

00:49:21.870 --> 00:49:25.180
So the first level
thinker is naive.

00:49:25.180 --> 00:49:27.576
He says, this is a great
company, let's buy the stock.

00:49:27.576 --> 00:49:29.700
The second level thinker
says it's a great company,

00:49:29.700 --> 00:49:31.700
but it's not as great as
everybody thinks it is.

00:49:31.700 --> 00:49:32.970
We better sell the stock.

00:49:32.970 --> 00:49:34.580
That's the difference
between being

00:49:34.580 --> 00:49:38.520
an average person and a
person with superior insight.

00:49:38.520 --> 00:49:44.820
By the way, most people
are not above average.

