than they were 20 years ago?

00:52:28.715 --> 00:52:31.890
HOWARD MARKS:
Well, look, I think

00:52:31.890 --> 00:52:35.080
there's a minor movement
toward indexation.

00:52:35.080 --> 00:52:38.080
It's not groundswell.

00:52:38.080 --> 00:52:42.000
There's still lots of money in
actively managed mutual funds

00:52:42.000 --> 00:52:48.010
where there's 2% a year of fees
and costs or one and a half.

00:52:48.010 --> 00:52:51.400
But I think there's more
in indexation every year.

00:52:51.400 --> 00:52:53.260
And that's probably appropriate.

00:52:53.260 --> 00:52:55.000
But I'll just turn i around.

00:52:55.000 --> 00:52:57.320
I'll leave you with a question.

00:52:57.320 --> 00:52:59.770
Why can't people
beat the market?

00:52:59.770 --> 00:53:02.060
Because the market's
pretty efficient.

00:53:02.060 --> 00:53:04.440
And market prices
most things right.

00:53:04.440 --> 00:53:07.000
And most people can't
find and identify

00:53:07.000 --> 00:53:10.165
and act on the times when the
market prices things wrong.

00:53:10.165 --> 00:53:12.040
That's why most people
can't beat the market.

00:53:12.040 --> 00:53:14.050
That's what I learned at
University of Chicago.

00:53:14.050 --> 00:53:16.520
And I think it's pretty true.

00:53:16.520 --> 00:53:20.260
So the reason for the
inability to beat the market

00:53:20.260 --> 00:53:21.520
is the markets efficiency.

00:53:21.520 --> 00:53:24.710
The markets efficiency comes
from the concerted efforts

00:53:24.710 --> 00:53:26.130
of thousands of
investors who are

00:53:26.130 --> 00:53:27.970
trying to find the bargains.

00:53:27.970 --> 00:53:30.530
What happens when
they stop trying?

00:53:30.530 --> 00:53:35.850
So when the interest
in active investment

00:53:35.850 --> 00:53:37.930
declines because
people give up on it

00:53:37.930 --> 00:53:40.400
and turn to passive investing
and all the analysts

00:53:40.400 --> 00:53:44.020
quick studying the
companies, then prices

00:53:44.020 --> 00:53:46.910
resume their deviation
from intrinsic value.

00:53:46.910 --> 00:53:50.970
Then it becomes possible
to beat the market again.

00:53:50.970 --> 00:53:54.880
So it's really paradoxical and,
I would say, counter-intuitive.

00:53:54.880 --> 00:53:57.830
But I don't think we
are close to that day.

00:53:57.830 --> 00:54:01.150
But in theory, there comes a
day when so little attention

00:54:01.150 --> 00:54:02.680
is being paid to
active investing

00:54:02.680 --> 00:54:06.071
that active investing
starts working again.

00:54:06.071 --> 00:54:06.570
Yes, sir.

00:54:06.570 --> 00:54:09.060
AUDIENCE: Thanks, Howard,
for coming for the talk.

00:54:09.060 --> 00:54:12.760
To talk about the difference
in value and the price,

00:54:12.760 --> 00:54:14.320
the other dimension is time.

00:54:14.320 --> 00:54:19.060
So how do you estimate the time
taking to [INAUDIBLE] to close?

00:54:19.060 --> 00:54:20.300
HOWARD MARKS: You never do.

00:54:20.300 --> 00:54:21.750
You never know.

00:54:21.750 --> 00:54:25.130
See, what he's saying-- again,
it's a very good question.

00:54:25.130 --> 00:54:28.920
And what we want
to do is we want

00:54:28.920 --> 00:54:31.480
to find things where the
intrinsic value is here

00:54:31.480 --> 00:54:33.070
and the price is here.

00:54:33.070 --> 00:54:35.885
So his question is, how
do we estimate the time

00:54:35.885 --> 00:54:39.310
that it's going to take
for the gap to close?

00:54:39.310 --> 00:54:42.130
And the answer is
there's no way to say.

00:54:42.130 --> 00:54:45.970
On occasion, there are
what we call catalysts.

00:54:45.970 --> 00:54:53.120
And one catalyst would be the
pending maturity of a bond.

00:54:53.120 --> 00:54:55.491
If a bond is going
to mature in 2012

00:54:55.491 --> 00:54:57.490
and it's selling at 60
because most people think

00:54:57.490 --> 00:54:59.650
it's going to go
bankrupt but we think

00:54:59.650 --> 00:55:03.500
it's going to pay
off at maturity,

00:55:03.500 --> 00:55:06.800
then the existence
of the maturity date

00:55:06.800 --> 00:55:10.460
is going to force the
convergence of price to value.

00:55:10.460 --> 00:55:17.220
Another catalyst today is
all these activist investors.

00:55:17.220 --> 00:55:18.180
They find the company.

00:55:18.180 --> 00:55:18.670
It's selling.

00:55:18.670 --> 00:55:20.100
They think the
interesting value is here.

00:55:20.100 --> 00:55:22.225
It's selling here because
the management is sub par

00:55:22.225 --> 00:55:23.933
and they're not doing
the right strategy.

00:55:23.933 --> 00:55:24.540
So they go in.

00:55:24.540 --> 00:55:25.682
They foment trouble.

00:55:25.682 --> 00:55:26.890
They try to get a board seat.

00:55:26.890 --> 00:55:29.910
They try to force the
management to do the right thing

00:55:29.910 --> 00:55:34.900
to course, to cause, the price
to converge with the value.

00:55:34.900 --> 00:55:37.010
So there are a few
catalyst in the world.

00:55:37.010 --> 00:55:38.770
But generally speaking,
you buy a stock.

00:55:38.770 --> 00:55:40.631
You hope-- you would
think it's worth here.

00:55:40.631 --> 00:55:41.380
The price is here.

00:55:41.380 --> 00:55:42.338
You hope it'll convert.

00:55:42.338 --> 00:55:45.170
But there's no way
to estimate the time.

00:55:45.170 --> 00:55:49.670
And that's the reason why being
too far ahead of your time

00:55:49.670 --> 00:55:51.890
is [INAUDIBLE] from
being wrong because it

00:55:51.890 --> 00:55:53.215
can take a long time.

00:55:53.215 --> 00:55:55.590
AUDIENCE: Would you always
look for presence of catalyst

00:55:55.590 --> 00:55:56.594
when you find a gap?

00:55:56.594 --> 00:55:58.010
HOWARD MARKS: There
aren't enough.

00:55:58.010 --> 00:55:59.290
I mean, it happens.

00:55:59.290 --> 00:56:02.580
Most of what we do is in
the fixed income world.

00:56:02.580 --> 00:56:05.390
And there are more catalysts
in the fixed income world

00:56:05.390 --> 00:56:07.700
than in the equity world.

00:56:07.700 --> 00:56:10.170
You find a stock.

00:56:10.170 --> 00:56:13.580
How many stocks you think
the activist investors

00:56:13.580 --> 00:56:14.750
go after a year?

00:56:14.750 --> 00:56:15.250
10?

00:56:15.250 --> 00:56:15.670
20?

00:56:15.670 --> 00:56:16.090
50?

00:56:16.090 --> 00:56:16.590
100?

00:56:16.590 --> 00:56:17.610
No more.

00:56:17.610 --> 00:56:19.510
There are thousands of stocks.

00:56:19.510 --> 00:56:22.627
So most stocks are never
going to get catalyzed.

00:56:22.627 --> 00:56:24.210
AUDIENCE: Curious
if you could tell us

00:56:24.210 --> 00:56:27.640
what it was like when you
were out raising money

00:56:27.640 --> 00:56:29.270
for Oak Tree in the early days.

00:56:29.270 --> 00:56:34.468
I would imagine that today
some clients are skeptical.

00:56:34.468 --> 00:56:35.842
But I would imagine
that it was--

00:56:35.842 --> 00:56:37.850
was it a lot different
for you back then?

00:56:37.850 --> 00:56:41.480
HOWARD MARKS: Well by the
time we started Oak Tree,

00:56:41.480 --> 00:56:44.530
it wasn't that hard because
we had a reputation.

00:56:44.530 --> 00:56:49.810
But when I started raising
money for our strategies--

00:56:49.810 --> 00:56:53.540
1978 junk bonds-- 90% of
investment organizations

00:56:53.540 --> 00:56:59.070
like Google had a
rule, a concrete rule,

00:56:59.070 --> 00:57:03.850
against any bond investing below
A or below investment grade,

00:57:03.850 --> 00:57:05.330
which is BBB.

00:57:05.330 --> 00:57:08.930
And of course, Moody said
it's an imprudent investment.

00:57:08.930 --> 00:57:12.040
So that was very,
very hard to overcome.

00:57:12.040 --> 00:57:15.425
But what you have to do is
you have to find a few people.

00:57:15.425 --> 00:57:17.260
You see, you have to
find a few people.

00:57:17.260 --> 00:57:19.430
You have to go say to
them you should do this

00:57:19.430 --> 00:57:21.810
because nobody else is.

00:57:21.810 --> 00:57:25.144
Because nobody else is doing
it, it's languishing cheap.

00:57:25.144 --> 00:57:26.560
You make no money
doing the things

00:57:26.560 --> 00:57:27.610
that everybody wants to do.

00:57:27.610 --> 00:57:29.026
You make money by
doing the things

00:57:29.026 --> 00:57:33.040
that nobody wants to do who
then turn out to have value.

00:57:33.040 --> 00:57:36.020
And if you say that message to
100 investors in the beginning,

00:57:36.020 --> 00:57:38.680
maybe 10 jump on board.

00:57:38.680 --> 00:57:40.740
After it works for a
while, then the rest

00:57:40.740 --> 00:57:43.970
come on, like the screen says.

00:57:43.970 --> 00:57:46.970
But hopefully, not too extreme.

00:57:46.970 --> 00:57:50.020
But the point is it was
very hard in the beginning.

00:57:50.020 --> 00:57:54.530
And in certain
foreign countries,

00:57:54.530 --> 00:57:57.210
it was even harder because in
certain foreign countries where

00:57:57.210 --> 00:58:01.589
the thinking is a little more
narrow than American thinking

00:58:01.589 --> 00:58:03.755
I always thought that if I
go into somebody's office

00:58:03.755 --> 00:58:05.879
and I say you should do
this because nobody else is

00:58:05.879 --> 00:58:09.550
they'd call the man in the
white coat to take me away.

00:58:09.550 --> 00:58:10.962
They don't understand.

00:58:10.962 --> 00:58:14.680
You know, I think that
Americans semi intuitively

00:58:14.680 --> 00:58:16.910
understand the value
of contrarianism

00:58:16.910 --> 00:58:18.810
and of being a maverick.

00:58:18.810 --> 00:58:21.760
But in many countries,
they just don't get it.

00:58:21.760 --> 00:58:23.940
So that's an
example, high yield.

00:58:23.940 --> 00:58:27.450
But then we started Oak
Tree in-- oh, no, no.

00:58:27.450 --> 00:58:28.690
That was at Citi.

00:58:28.690 --> 00:58:32.530
In '85, I switched from Citi to
Trust Company of the West, TCW.

00:58:32.530 --> 00:58:35.910
And in '88, we brought out
the first distress debt fund.

00:58:35.910 --> 00:58:39.030
Now we're not
investing in companies

00:58:39.030 --> 00:58:40.580
that have a risk of default.

00:58:40.580 --> 00:58:43.850
We're investing in bonds
that are either in default

00:58:43.850 --> 00:58:46.025
or sure to be.

00:58:46.025 --> 00:58:47.650
And people would say,
well, how can you

00:58:47.650 --> 00:58:49.990
possibly make money
investing in the bonds

00:58:49.990 --> 00:58:52.410
of bankrupt companies?

00:58:52.410 --> 00:59:00.000
And we had to explain to them
that if a creditor of a company

00:59:00.000 --> 00:59:03.280
doesn't get paid the interest
in principle as promised,

00:59:03.280 --> 00:59:05.780
they have a claim against
the value of the company.

00:59:05.780 --> 00:59:09.750
And they exert that claim in
a process called bankruptcy.

00:59:09.750 --> 00:59:12.160
And in bankruptcy,
to oversimplify

00:59:12.160 --> 00:59:14.690
and over generalize, the
old owners are wiped out.

00:59:14.690 --> 00:59:17.420
And the old creditors
become the new owners.

00:59:17.420 --> 00:59:20.790
And if you bought an ownership
stake through the debt

00:59:20.790 --> 00:59:24.910
for--what-- for less than it's
worth, then you make money.

00:59:24.910 --> 00:59:31.130
And we've made about 23% a
year for 28 years investing

00:59:31.130 --> 00:59:37.160
in distressed debt before
fees without any leverage.

00:59:37.160 --> 00:59:39.240
So that's pretty astronomical.

00:59:39.240 --> 00:59:39.740
Why?

00:59:39.740 --> 00:59:42.420
Because from time to
time in distress debt

00:59:42.420 --> 00:59:44.990
you get to buy things for
less than they're worth.

00:59:44.990 --> 00:59:47.630
And in fact because
other people are fleeing

00:59:47.630 --> 00:59:50.070
from the bankruptcy,
maybe you get

00:59:50.070 --> 00:59:53.620
them to buy them for a lot
less than they're worth.

00:59:53.620 --> 00:59:55.760
So it's very challenging.

00:59:55.760 --> 01:00:01.250
But you can't
convince everybody.

01:00:01.250 --> 01:00:04.850
But if you can
explain the merits

01:00:04.850 --> 01:00:10.407
and tell the story clearly,
and concisely, and persuasively

01:00:10.407 --> 01:00:11.490
then you get some clients.

01:00:11.490 --> 01:00:13.010
And then, if you
get good results,

01:00:13.010 --> 01:00:16.205
then you get more clients.

01:00:16.205 --> 01:00:18.230
AUDIENCE: Thank you,
Howard, for your talk.

01:00:18.230 --> 01:00:19.290
One question.

01:00:19.290 --> 01:00:23.300
Buffet, in '99, said that if he
was running very small amounts

01:00:23.300 --> 01:00:26.310
of money he would be able
to find lots of bargains

01:00:26.310 --> 01:00:28.460
and beat the market
by 50% and he

01:00:28.460 --> 01:00:30.415
would use the word guaranteed.

01:00:30.415 --> 01:00:31.790
I presume he meant
that there are

01:00:31.790 --> 01:00:36.630
a lot of inefficiencies in the
small capitalization stocks.

01:00:36.630 --> 01:00:40.910
One thing that kind of surprises
me is if someone, an analyst,

01:00:40.910 --> 01:00:42.870
willing to work
hard on his own, not

01:00:42.870 --> 01:00:46.330
in an institution, the word
of distress debt investing

01:00:46.330 --> 01:00:50.002
is kind of shut out, even
for the value investor.

01:00:50.002 --> 01:00:51.960
[INAUDIBLE] with a lot
of technicalities and it

01:00:51.960 --> 01:00:55.597
seems like the big institution
has a lot of advantage there.

01:00:55.597 --> 01:01:00.330
Are there such inefficiencies
that are kind of shut out

01:01:00.330 --> 01:01:03.230
to the institutions but the
small investor willing to work

01:01:03.230 --> 01:01:06.190
hard can find inefficiencies
in the debt world?

01:01:06.190 --> 01:01:12.730
HOWARD MARKS: Well I think
that the small guy can even

01:01:12.730 --> 01:01:15.050
be active in distressed debt.

01:01:15.050 --> 01:01:18.230
He can't get enough bonds to
get a seat at the creditors

01:01:18.230 --> 01:01:20.190
committee table or have a voice.

01:01:20.190 --> 01:01:24.080
But he can still
find superior values.

01:01:24.080 --> 01:01:27.240
You know, so what I was saying
in answer to your question

01:01:27.240 --> 01:01:30.880
is that if you get some accounts
and you have good performance,

01:01:30.880 --> 01:01:32.550
you'll get more accounts.

01:01:32.550 --> 01:01:35.320
So that goes a little
further because what I really

01:01:35.320 --> 01:01:37.340
say is that if you
have good performance,

01:01:37.340 --> 01:01:38.900
you'll get more money.

01:01:38.900 --> 01:01:41.610
And eventually, if you let
that process become unchecked,

01:01:41.610 --> 01:01:45.050
if you get more money,
you'll have bad performance.

01:01:45.050 --> 01:01:48.120
And this is one of the
conundrums in our business.

01:01:54.269 --> 01:01:55.310
So you have to halt that.

01:01:55.310 --> 01:01:59.230
But the truth of the matter
is that the little guy

01:01:59.230 --> 01:02:04.270
has an advantage as long as
he's willing to stay small.

01:02:04.270 --> 01:02:09.310
Many people are not because in
the short run, the more money

01:02:09.310 --> 01:02:16.280
you manage when you get
fees, it's a great lure

01:02:16.280 --> 01:02:17.250
to take on more money.

01:02:17.250 --> 01:02:20.030
But you have to
stop it at a point

01:02:20.030 --> 01:02:22.610
before it starts running
your performance.

01:02:22.610 --> 01:02:25.970
Now, for the data
scientists among us,

01:02:25.970 --> 01:02:35.860
I always like to point out that
if I worked at Firestone Tires

01:02:35.860 --> 01:02:37.830
and I developed a new
tire, and I wanted

01:02:37.830 --> 01:02:40.870
to know how far it would
go, I would put it on a car

01:02:40.870 --> 01:02:42.760
and run it until
it blew up, right.

01:02:42.760 --> 01:02:45.250
That's called
destructive testing.

01:02:45.250 --> 01:02:48.460
But as an investor with clients
and a fiduciary responsibility,

01:02:48.460 --> 01:02:51.890
I don't have the luxury of
doing destructive testing.

01:02:51.890 --> 01:02:53.859
So I can't add more.

01:02:53.859 --> 01:02:55.400
People always say
to me, well, what's

01:02:55.400 --> 01:02:57.740
the limit on how much
money you can invest well?

01:02:57.740 --> 01:03:01.780
And I can't find out by
running into the wall.

01:03:01.780 --> 01:03:03.676
I have to stop this
side of the wall.

01:03:03.676 --> 01:03:05.050
One of the
interesting lessons is

01:03:05.050 --> 01:03:06.790
that if you stop
this side of the wall

01:03:06.790 --> 01:03:10.520
then you never find out
where the wall really is.

01:03:10.520 --> 01:03:11.800
But that's what we have to do.

01:03:15.050 --> 01:03:16.140
So you have to stop.

01:03:16.140 --> 01:03:18.820
And I believe that
the person who

01:03:18.820 --> 01:03:25.420
has a big brain, and a little
money, and a lot of time,

01:03:25.420 --> 01:03:31.350
and exceptional insight
can find great bargains.

01:03:31.350 --> 01:03:35.000
But that's a pretty
daunting list.

01:03:35.000 --> 01:03:39.815
And I don't think that Buffett's
guarantee necessarily extents

01:03:39.815 --> 01:03:41.203
to everybody in this room.

01:03:51.346 --> 01:03:54.740
AUDIENCE: Do you see any
unhealthy trends in valuation

01:03:54.740 --> 01:03:57.180
in the market today the
same way [INAUDIBLE]

01:03:57.180 --> 01:03:58.430
was valued in the past?

01:03:58.430 --> 01:04:10.400
HOWARD MARKS: Yes, I do
because the menu extends.

01:04:10.400 --> 01:04:11.920
What we call the
capital market line

01:04:11.920 --> 01:04:14.940
extends from what's
called the risk free rate.

01:04:14.940 --> 01:04:17.820
The risk free rate is the
rate, generally speaking,

01:04:17.820 --> 01:04:20.140
on the 30 day treasury bill.

01:04:20.140 --> 01:04:24.140
And of course, if you can
get 3% on the risk free rate,

01:04:24.140 --> 01:04:27.104
then in order to tie up your
money for five years in a five

01:04:27.104 --> 01:04:28.270
year treasury you want four.

01:04:28.270 --> 01:04:30.140
And to get it 10
years, you want five.

01:04:30.140 --> 01:04:34.740
And if you can get 10 years on
a government security of 5%,

01:04:34.740 --> 01:04:37.310
then in order to go into a
corporate security, which

01:04:37.310 --> 01:04:39.230
has some credit risk,
you would demand six.

01:04:39.230 --> 01:04:41.380
And to go into a high
yield bond, you demand 12

01:04:41.380 --> 01:04:42.620
and so forth.

01:04:42.620 --> 01:04:46.290
So there's a kind of a process
called equilibration, which

01:04:46.290 --> 01:04:49.560
makes things line up in terms
of relative risk and return

01:04:49.560 --> 01:04:52.880
but always pegged from
the risk free rate.

01:04:52.880 --> 01:04:55.030
Today, the risk
free rate is zero.

01:04:55.030 --> 01:04:59.350
So everything that I just
named, this capital market line,

01:04:59.350 --> 01:05:01.900
has had a parallel
downward shift.

01:05:01.900 --> 01:05:08.250
So before the
crisis, [INAUDIBLE]

01:05:08.250 --> 01:05:10.930
mentioned about the fact
that I turned bearish.

01:05:10.930 --> 01:05:14.380
All my money was in
was in treasuries.

01:05:14.380 --> 01:05:17.400
All the money that I had outside
of Oak Tree was in treasuries.

01:05:17.400 --> 01:05:21.082
And I was getting 6 1/2% for
one, two, three, four, five,

01:05:21.082 --> 01:05:22.870
six year maturities.

01:05:22.870 --> 01:05:25.880
I was getting income and safety.

01:05:25.880 --> 01:05:27.100
Today, you have a choice.

01:05:27.100 --> 01:05:30.590
Income or safety because
the things today that

01:05:30.590 --> 01:05:33.030
are highly safe pay no income.

01:05:33.030 --> 01:05:35.104
You know, and if
you go to Fidelity--

01:05:35.104 --> 01:05:36.020
conduct an experiment.

01:05:36.020 --> 01:05:40.220
Go to Fidelity or Vanguard
or a big mutual fund firm

01:05:40.220 --> 01:05:42.820
and go online and look at
their menu of offerings

01:05:42.820 --> 01:05:48.310
and what is the current net
yield after fees and expenses.

01:05:48.310 --> 01:05:51.680
And you'll see that for
money market and short term

01:05:51.680 --> 01:05:54.640
treasuries, and maybe
intermediate treasury,

01:05:54.640 --> 01:05:56.680
the yield is zero.

01:05:56.680 --> 01:05:57.930
So just think.

01:05:57.930 --> 01:06:01.810
The guy is watching the
Super Bowl in his undershirt.

01:06:01.810 --> 01:06:03.430
He gets a statement
from Fidelity.

01:06:03.430 --> 01:06:08.840
He opens it up, and it says the
yield on your fund is now zero.

01:06:08.840 --> 01:06:09.660
He grabs the phone.

01:06:09.660 --> 01:06:11.220
He calls the 800 number.

01:06:11.220 --> 01:06:13.300
He says get me out of that
fund that yields zero,

01:06:13.300 --> 01:06:16.260
and put me in the
one that yields six.

01:06:16.260 --> 01:06:18.710
And he becomes a high
yield bond investor.

01:06:18.710 --> 01:06:20.520
He has no idea why.

01:06:20.520 --> 01:06:22.340
He doesn't know what
a high yield bond is.

01:06:22.340 --> 01:06:24.575
He doesn't understand
what the dangers are.

01:06:24.575 --> 01:06:28.050
He doesn't understand how to
pick a high yield bond manager.

01:06:28.050 --> 01:06:32.340
But he's seduced by
that 6% versus zero.

01:06:32.340 --> 01:06:35.100
And all around the
investment world

01:06:35.100 --> 01:06:37.920
today, people are
chasing return.

01:06:37.920 --> 01:06:39.660
They don't like the
low returns that are

01:06:39.660 --> 01:06:41.070
available on safe instruments.

01:06:41.070 --> 01:06:43.690
They're going for the gusto.

01:06:43.690 --> 01:06:45.490
They're going for
riskier instruments.

01:06:45.490 --> 01:06:49.020
And they're doing it mindlessly.

01:06:49.020 --> 01:06:52.510
And I promised you I'd
mention some memos.

01:06:52.510 --> 01:06:53.940
I forgot to do that.

01:06:53.940 --> 01:06:57.910
But if you go back, I wrote one
in March of '07 called The Race

01:06:57.910 --> 01:06:59.480
To The Bottom.

01:06:59.480 --> 01:07:01.590
And I talked about
the fact that when

01:07:01.590 --> 01:07:04.150
people are, number one,
eager to invest and, number

01:07:04.150 --> 01:07:08.060
two, not sufficiently risk
conscious they do risky things.

01:07:08.060 --> 01:07:09.890
And when people do
risky things, the market

01:07:09.890 --> 01:07:11.290
becomes a risky place.

01:07:11.290 --> 01:07:13.230
And that's why Buffett
says, the less prudence

01:07:13.230 --> 01:07:14.990
with which others
conduct their affairs,

01:07:14.990 --> 01:07:16.448
the greater the
prudence with which

01:07:16.448 --> 01:07:17.980
we must conduct our own affairs.

01:07:17.980 --> 01:07:21.030
And that is going on
now to some extent

01:07:21.030 --> 01:07:24.410
because people can't get a good
return from safe instruments.

01:07:24.410 --> 01:07:27.300
They're going into the risky
ones, and they're bidding.

01:07:27.300 --> 01:07:31.760
You know, so there's
a race to the bottom.

01:07:31.760 --> 01:07:33.510
It's like an auction.

01:07:33.510 --> 01:07:37.022
Now if you want to buy a
painting at Sotheby's, there's

01:07:37.022 --> 01:07:38.980
an auction, and the
painting goes to the person

01:07:38.980 --> 01:07:41.940
who pays the highest price.

01:07:41.940 --> 01:07:45.339
But in the investment world,
it's a reverse auction.

01:07:45.339 --> 01:07:46.880
Well sometimes you
pay highest price,

01:07:46.880 --> 01:07:49.170
but sometimes you
bid in lowest return.

01:07:49.170 --> 01:07:54.620
So there's a bond that's going
to be issued by a company.

01:07:54.620 --> 01:07:57.510
I say I demand 7% interest.

01:07:57.510 --> 01:07:59.970
And this fellow says,
no, I'll take six.

01:07:59.970 --> 01:08:02.910
And that guy says,
I'll take five.

01:08:02.910 --> 01:08:05.340
I say I want protective
covenants to make sure

01:08:05.340 --> 01:08:08.800
that the company can't do
things that ruins its own credit

01:08:08.800 --> 01:08:09.760
worthiness.

01:08:09.760 --> 01:08:11.520
He says I'll do it
with less covenants.

01:08:11.520 --> 01:08:14.960
And that guy says, I'll
do it with no covenants.

01:08:14.960 --> 01:08:16.149
What happens?

01:08:16.149 --> 01:08:19.420
The bond is issued at
5% with no covenants.

01:08:19.420 --> 01:08:21.290
And that's the
race to the bottom.

01:08:21.290 --> 01:08:23.569
And anybody who
participates in that bond

01:08:23.569 --> 01:08:26.370
probably could be
making a mistake.

01:08:26.370 --> 01:08:27.870
And that's going on now.

01:08:27.870 --> 01:08:34.740
Not to the same terrible extent
that it was in '06 and '07.

01:08:34.740 --> 01:08:38.880
But you got to be careful today.

01:08:38.880 --> 01:08:41.080
Oak Tree's model for
the last 3 and 1/2 years

01:08:41.080 --> 01:08:43.390
has been move forward
but with caution.

01:08:43.390 --> 01:08:46.290
Caution has to be a
very important component

01:08:46.290 --> 01:08:49.749
of everybody's actions today.

01:08:49.749 --> 01:08:51.540
Well thank you very
much for being with me.

01:08:51.540 --> 01:08:52.850
And I hope you enjoyed it.

01:08:52.850 --> 01:08:56.244
And when I think of more
stuff, I'll come back.

